# Grid theme horizon beam on login page

## Summary

The grid theme's decorative "horizon" beam (`[data-skin="grid"] .app-main::after`) — a fixed-position 2px glowing line at `top: 40vh` — cuts across the vertically-centered login card on the login page. The grid floor (`::before`) also uses `z-index: 0` and can partially show behind the card.

## Root Cause

`grid.css` (lines 93–117) defines two fixed-position pseudo-elements on `.app-main`:

- **`::after`** — a glowing cyan horizon beam at `top: 40vh` with a horizontal gradient and pulsing animation (`grid-horizon`).
- **`::before`** — a perspective grid floor anchored at the bottom with animated scrolling grid lines (`grid-floor`).

These are designed for content pages where `.app-main` has enough internal content to position them out of the visible card area. On the login page, the `.login-card` is vertically centered via flexbox, placing it at roughly `50vh + nav-height`, which the horizon beam crosses.

## Fix

Added an override in `login.css` (which only loads on the login page) that hides both pseudo-elements when `.login-page` is present inside `.app-main`:

```css
[data-skin="grid"] .app-main:has(.login-page)::after,
[data-skin="grid"] .app-main:has(.login-page)::before {
  display: none;
}
```

The `:has()` scoping prevents affecting other pages — the grid theme's effects remain on all content pages.

## Implications

- This is a theme-specific override. If other themes add similar decorative pseudo-elements, they may also need login-page overrides.
- The fix is purely visual — the beam and grid floor are `pointer-events: none` decorations, so hiding them has no functional impact.
- `:has()` is well-supported in modern browsers (Chrome 105+, Safari 15.4+, Firefox 103+) and the project targets modern web runtimes.
